<ul id="poptab">
<li class="active">
<h4>biography</h4>
<br />
<center><h3>the file</h3></center>
<div id="bio"><p>&#9642; <b>FULL NAME:</b> Zane Balthazar Lennon
<p>&#9642; <b>ALIASES/NICKNAMES:</b> Beatle, Balts 
<p>&#9642; <b>DATE OF BIRTH:</b> September 19, 1986
<p>&#9642; <b>PROFESSION:</b> Forger
<p>&#9642; <b>SEXUALITY:</b>  Zane considers himself indiscriminate, meaning it doesn't matter if it's a man, or a woman. If he finds you attractive, he will use his charm to bring you back to his bed. He's also never been one for long term relationships, and prefers a casual fling to something more serious. In his line of work, attachments tend to be dangerous, and being unattached just works for him.
<p>&#9642; <b>BODY TYPE:</b> 6' in height, and roughly 180 lbs. He's not skinny, per se, but neither is he built. What little weight he does have is all muscle.
<p>&#9642; <b>CLOTHING:</b> If anything, Zane is a creature of comfort. Meaning you're more likely to find him in jeans, and a t-shirt, than some three piece suit. Most of his wardrobe consists of designer jeans, and t-shirts in multiple shades of black, blue, grey, and green, as well as the occasional pair of sweats. Of course, if the situation calls for it, he does have suits that he will wear. He will just bitch, and moan, about being uncomfortable and out of his element.
<p>&#9642; <b>DISTINCTIVE FEATURES:</b> Upon first glance, one tends to notice Zane's eyes, as they tend to cycle through various shades of green depending on his mood. The darker they are, the more likely it is that you will end up flat on your back. He also has a unique celtic tattoo that covers most of his right arm, and shoulder. After his first forging job went south, and he was shot, he decided that the tattoo was a good way to hide the very ugly scar that came from the wound. It is one of his own creations, consisting of celtic knots, celtic dragons, and basic tribal elements. There is also a miniaturized version of Van Gogh's Starry Night portrait on the left side of his chest, as a reminder of his mother, and his roots.
<p>&#9642; <b>PERSONALITY:</b> Zane likes to think he's just a simple person, just looking for some fun outside the boundaries of the law. Although he knows that there is no such thing as being simple, should anyone ask him, he will always deny he's anything but. His out-going personality tends to conflict with that fact. Making things worse, is the fact that at times, he can be quiet, almost to the point of being shy. No one really notices it, because he's always interacting with people, making certain everyone knows he's quite comfortable in his own skin. Most of the time, the struggle between being his usual self, and the shy, scared little boy, is under control. But when faced with a situation that makes him doubt himself, the war flares up, and those times, he wishes for the comfort of his sketchpad.
<p>He also considers himself quite an adventurous person, almost bordering on restless, preferring not to spend too much time in one place. Having spent a majority of his life in one city, Zane always wanted to travel, and see what else the world offered. Staying in one place meant he easily got bored, and when he became bored, trouble usually followed. On the flip side, his bouts of boredom tend to lend themselves to his determination, and perfectionism. When left with his own thoughts, Zane tends to look over all his previous works, finding each and every little flaw, and wanting to do better. Each flaw only spurs him to do better, and that determination tends to overflow into whichever job he may currently be working.
<p>Unfortunately, he's also easily frustrated. Especially when a job doesn't go his way, or when he has to deal with incompetent people. Zane tries very hard not to let people, or jobs, get to him, as he prefers people to think of him as easygoing, and not some sort of hard ass. Most of the time, he can get along with anyone who crosses his path. The instant they prove to him otherwise, he finds himself seeing them through a different lens, and as such, finds himself getting frustrated at the drop of a hat. Time, unfortunately, is the only thing that calms him down.
<p>&#9642; <b>LIKES:</b> Van Gogh, post-impressionist paintings, Beethoven, Mozart, replicating his art idols, being spontaneous, art museums, travelling, learning new languages, drawing
<p>&#9642; <b>DISLIKES:</b> staying in one place for long periods of time, renaissance painters, Italy, sitting in complete silence, three piece suits, formal parties, laziness
<p>&#9642; <b>HOPES AND DREAMS:</b> being the best forger there is, making enough from dream-sharing that he can enjoy painting and drawing without worry, making his mother proud, one day accepting the fact that loyalty & perfection aren't weaknesses, owning the real starry night portrait and not just his own forgery
<p>&#9642; <b>FEARS:</b> being alone, becoming a failure, death, his parents finding out just what he does, disappointing people (and his own mother)
<p>&#9642; <b>STRENGTHS:</b> being a perfectionist, attention to detail, loyalty to those he considers friends, his determination, he's a damn good shot
<p>&#9642; <b>WEAKNESSES:</b> his arrogance, his quick temper, being a perfectionist, his loyalty, his determination, his thrill seeking nature
</div>
<p>
<center><h3>dreamsharing</h3></center>
<div id="hc"><p>Zane found out about dream-sharing from his partner in crime, Michel. While they tended to work real world jobs, he quickly found himself becoming bored, and wanting something that would actually push his skills. Until one day, Michel offered him a new world, where his forgeries could take on a whole new level, and where he was less likely to become bored. Curiosity killed the cat, and given the fact it was dangerous, just added to the thrill. It wasn't something he was going to turn down. Not when it could only push himself to become better.
</div>
<p>
<center><h3>history</h3></center>
<p>As the only child of  rich, American ex-pats in London, Zane spent most of his time being shuffled between nannies, and chaperones. His mother tried to be a parent to him, taking him to art museums, and the likes, but in the end, she preferred spending her time alone, with her own dying art career than taking care of her only child. His father, on the other hand, made it perfectly clear that he would have nothing to do with him, other than to make certain he was well educated, and had money available to him for whatever he desired. This hands off approach left him constantly trying to find ways not only to entertain himself, but to garner some sort of attention, whether that was from those who looked after him, or his actual parents. When his mother did actually decide to be a parent, they would spend hours upon hours at the different art museums in London, and one long weekend, took in the museums of Paris. That was the summer before his life started upon the path that led him to the life of crime. It was also when he'd decided to take up drawing, and art, seriously. Much to his mother's delight.
<p>During his last years in school, Zane found out that his <i>talents</i> for art, also favoured recreating identification cards, and drivers licenses. The first time was for a classmate, a boy who wanted to be old enough to enter a club without anyone having to actually question the legality of his ID.  It wasn't his best work, but it passed the bouncer inspection, and had he known how popular his <i>skills</i> were going to be, he would have actually charged for the first one. After that, word got around through school, that if you wanted an ID made, Zane Lennon was the person to speak to. The first few times were his close friends, wanting their licenses to make them old enough to go clubbing, or buy alcohol, or whatever it was they wanted to do. He'd learned it was best not to ask any questions. Plausible deniability, and all that. When random kids from their school started making inquires, he knew he had something good. It was then that he decided to charge, rather handsomely, for his work. He also decided to actually put an effort into it, knowing that one bad word, and his reputation would be ruined. The money wasn't something he <i>needed</i>, per se, but it was something he enjoyed. Even more so, knowing his father would have had a fit if he knew what his son was up to.
<p>By the time he hit eighteen, and officially graduated from school, his reputation had already preceded him. Some of Zane's contacts had passed his name along to some <i>friends</i>, and those friends wanted his particular skill set for a few jobs. Of course, they would pay him, and more than he would charge for his regular work, but they also required him to learn a few new skills. Mostly how to shoot, and if possible, the fine art of thievery. Forgery was something he was good at. Thieving wasn't something he'd honestly thought about. And learning how to fire a gun? It had crossed his mind a time or two. Especially when he'd been forced to attend some of the social functions that his father held. But that was all it had been. Just a passing thought. Then again, he enjoyed the money, and the actual craft of forging, and if he could make a career out of it, he would. Learning how to use a gun had been easy, and something he picked up relatively quickly. The thieving? The first time he tried to pick someone's pocket, he almost ended up arrested. But after getting a few tips, and practising on some of his friends, had it down pat, as well. But it would never been his strength. Not like recreating a Rembrandt, in all its glory.
<p>His first job as a thief slash forger had been an utter nightmare. Zane would remember it for the rest of his life. Not to mention the scar that he got from being shot. The boss of his crew had thought it would be a good idea to screw over their client, and in the end, most of them had ended up either wounded, or worse. He hadn't stuck around long enough to find out what happened to the others. It was then that he decided to work by himself, instead of aligning himself with some group. Too many people, too many conflicting ideas, came with working in a group. Working by himself meant he was only accountable to himself. It also meant he would keep all of the money. Being a solo act wasn't easy, but after almost a year, he'd made a name for himself, and anyone who wanted passports, birth certificates, or any other sort of forgery done, knew exactly who to go do. He was actually quite proud of himself, and of the work he did. Though, he still refused to let his parents in on the exact details, preferring a well crafted lie to the truth. It wasn't as if they actually cared what he did. Just as long as he didn't end up dead somewhere.
<p>Meeting Michel, two years after leaving school, was another one of his life changing moments. Zane had been hired to work on some passports, something he could almost do blindfolded, if he were honest with himself, and the plan was to meet at one of the nightclubs in Soho. That part of London wasn't his usual hangout, but he knew enough about the area to be weary. He also knew enough about people to be leery of meeting in a nightclub, to discuss business of all things. But a job was a job, and the man was willing to pay a little extra than his usual clients, so who was he to refuse. Upon seeing the man, his first impression had been that of a businessman, not unlike his own father. His usual clients never came to meetings in three piece suits, and looked like they'd just stepped out of some building near Canary Wharf. But the man was willing to pay, and Zane was more than willing to offer his services. For a price, of course. But they'd never gotten to that point in their conversation. The club was raided, and while he was a bit fuzzy on the details, he did remember Michel making certain they both made it out of the club in one piece. 
<p>He'd always told himself he would never work with someone else again, would never rely on anyone other than himself to get out of a situation. But Michel changed his opinion on working with someone, and when he'd suggested they work together again sometime, he agreed, wondering if the man was being polite, or if he truly meant it. It hadn't taken more than a few weeks before his mobile was ringing, and Michel offered him yet another job. Zane had actually been hesitant about it, but when he'd been told the details, knew it wasn't something he could turn down. The job was one of his easiest yet, and he had actually enjoyed working with Michel. Not to mention the multiple zeros that ended up in his bank account. Though, it was one job, and then it was back to the grind. He wasn't cut out for working in a group, and while he was bored of working in London, he knew it meant safety. He knew the city like the back of his hand. Though, he wasn't opposed to working with his new partner. Especially, if it meant getting out of the city. Zane wasn't sure he could trust Michel, but they worked well together. Better than any of the people from his first crew. 
<p>Maybe that was a sign. Or maybe, he was just being childish. But he'd agreed to travel with Michel. As long as he could work a few jobs on the side. Old habits die hard, after all. Zane actually decided against working any jobs that didn't involve his new partner when he almost lost his life at the hands of some thug. It wasn't his fault the man was younger than he looked, and he hadn't given any specifics other than what he needed. Working with a partner wasn't so bad, after that, and he found himself slowly trusting Michel. Soon, they never worked without the other, and their partnership was one he actually felt safe in. Like he'd felt back in London. Michel was the older brother he'd never had, and actually looked to him as such. He refused to go anywhere without him. When he was invited into the world of dream-sharing, Zane knew his life would once again change. For the better? He hadn't a clue. But he knew Michel wouldn't willingly put them in harm's way. They'd made a name for themselves in the real world, and he had a feeling the same would happen in the dream-sharing world. And his feelings were very rarely wrong.
<p>

<br /> <br /><br />
</li>

<li>
<h4>headcanons</h4>
<br />
<center><h3>trivia</h3></center>
<div id="hc"><p>&#9642; Zane is actually ambidextrous, and while he's never kept it a secret, he's never announced it either. If people watch him long enough, it's something they will pick up. 
<p>&#9642; He's also become a natural at reading people, finding their flaws, and weaknesses, just by watching them. 
<p>&#9642; He also has this really bad habit of pacing when stressed, or needing to think. Many times, he's been told not to, but it's something he can't help. It's just a part of him, like his quick temper. 
<p>&#9642; There's also this quirk about him where he's more likely to shoot first, ask questions never. But that only happens when he feels like he's been fucked over one too many times by the same person. Or when he's just had enough of a situation.
</div>
